				\begin{document}$$\psi$$\end{document} represents the incidence angle of the light. As indicated in (2), unique variations in the received signal may originate from the LED, driver module, channel, or receiver. However, commercial hardware components, such as the driver module and receiver, are specifically designed for communication, which means manufacturing tolerances have minimal impact on performance. In contrast, LEDs contain a severe nonlinearity due to their primary purpose of lighting. Thus, the following sections focus on identifying the subtle differences within the LED, given the responses of the driver module, channel, and receiver are consistent (same driver module and receiver, fixed distance).

As depicted in the dotted box of Fig. 1, the differences between LED devices can be intricately analyzed through the carrier transport process. Electrons are injected from the N-type contact and holes from the P-type contact, both in quantities proportional to the input signal \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$x(t)$$\end{document}. Electrons traverse the n-type GaN layer into the conduction band, while holes are injected into the valence band through the p-type GaN layer. Driven by the electric field, these carriers migrate toward the multi-quantum well (MQW) region. The electron blocking layer (EBL), situated between the MQW and the p-type GaN layer, plays a critical role in suppressing electron overflow from the MQW, thereby enhancing carrier confinement. Within the MQW, confined electrons and holes accumulate and recombine radiatively, emitting photons. These photons propagate through the epitaxial layers, culminating in light emission from the LED structure.

