Extracted fingerprint heatmap patterns for the 15 LED-based transmitters using the initial PSD dataset.

To further validate the effectiveness of the proposed physics-based feature, we compared it with traditional deep learning classification methods and existing circuit model features. Convolutional neural network (CNN) and long short-term memory (LSTM) methods were implemented on the noised dataset (30 dB) to train the classifiers. The CNN processes one-dimensional feature vectors with an input size of 400, employing two convolutional layers with kernels generating 16 and 32 feature maps, respectively. These layers are followed by batch normalization, ReLU activation, and max-pooling with a size and stride of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$2 \times 1$$\end{document}. The training was conducted using the Adam optimizer for 30 epochs with an initial learning rate of 0.001. The LSTM network also uses a 400-dimensional input, followed by a single LSTM layer with six hidden units configured to output only the last sequence state. A ReLU activation layer and a fully connected classification layer were appended. Both networks utilized a shuffled training dataset for robust performance evaluation. Furthermore, comparisons were conducted with existing circuit features21 classified using the same KNN classifier. It is worth noting that the KNN classifier was also trained using the same 15,000 samples (30 dB) to ensure a fair comparison with the deep learning methods.
